The « Green Deal » European
NEW YORK – Europe did it.
The « Green Deal for Europe » announced by the European Commission is to date the first global sustainable development plan decided by a major world region.
It thus becomes a benchmark for the entire world – a guide to the transformation towards a prosperous, socially inclusive, and ecologically sustainable economy, a first agenda for all to follow.
Naturally, the task ahead for Europeans is impressive.
Even the reading of the documents that have just been made public is: a profusion at first glance of plans, consultations, regulatory frameworks, laws, budgets, and diplomacy, a large number of related subjects ranging from energy to transport, from food to industry.
Its detractors will mock European bureaucracy.
But it is a bureaucracy in the best Weberian sense: it is rational.
Sustainable development objectives are clearly stated, targets are defined according to goals submitted to a timeline, and programs and procedures are adapted to these targets.
In general, the declared ambition is to achieve carbon neutrality (net-zero greenhouse gas emissions) by 2050, to implement a circular economy that puts an end to destructive pollution caused by plastics and other petrochemical derivatives, pesticides, and toxic waste, and to establish a "farm-to-table" food system that does not kill people by making them eat overly processed industrial products, nor the earth with unsustainable agricultural practices.
And the European Commission understands that the method for achieving this must rely on citizens themselves.
Again, detractors will consider the announcements of public consultations as mere window dressing for empty talkers.
But talk of idle chatter won't resonate with French President Emmanuel Macron, who faced more than a year of escalating protests turning to riots, or Chilean President Sebastián Piñera, whose country suddenly erupted in unrest this autumn after a slight increase in metro ticket prices.
Both Macron and Piñera are convinced of the necessity of ecological change.
Both have committed their countries to carbon neutrality by 2050.
And both are desperately trying to organize or structure a public consultation, but after the fact.
American neo-liberals will once again mock and assert that the "market" will know how to remedy climate change.
But just look at the United States today.
If neo-liberalism treats the planet as it has treated American infrastructure, we all have something to worry about.
Arriving at an airport in the United States, you have to endure elevators, broken escalators, stranded shuttle buses, taxis that don't arrive, non-existent rail connections, highways in such poor condition that they cannot be driven on, replaced by detours.
The reason for these malfunctions is simple: corruption.
Each U.S. election cycle costs billions of dollars, if not more, and the funding comes from billionaires, major oil companies, the military-industrial complex, the healthcare industry lobby, and interest groups determined to lower taxes and protect the status quo at all costs.
The market solutions are a joke when politics is subject to all the influences that emanate from it, as is the case in the United States.
The European Green Deal shows what a government should be like, and not one subordinate to corporate interests.
The European Green Deal actually demonstrates the success of European social democracy (in its operational sense, not narrowly partisan).
<p>An mixed economy, which combines markets, state regulatory power, public sector, and civil society, will pursue a mixed strategy: public goals, public investments in infrastructure, private investments in industrial transformation, research and development missions based on public-private partnerships, and an informed population.</p>
<p>Actually, it's the most sophisticated industrial policy at its level.</p>
<p>(I recently indicated, in broad terms, what a social-democratic Green New Deal would look like for the United States.)</p>
<p>We have reasons to be optimistic.</p>
<p>The most important point is that the advanced technologies that will allow the creation of an advanced decarbonized, resource-efficient, and therefore ecologically sustainable economy exist, at the commercial or pre-commercial stage.</p>
<p>In combining renewable energy, digital technologies, advanced materials, and collaborative economics in transportation or other infrastructures, we can decarbonize the energy system, transition to a circular economy, and drastically reduce primary resource flows.</p>
<p>But to do this, we must overcome three major challenges.</p>
<p>The first is to overcome the interests that seek to maintain the status quo.</p>
<p>The major oil companies will need to absorb losses, but workers in the sector and mining regions should receive compensation, in the form of income supports, retraining, and other public aids.</p>
<p>The European plan rightly claims a "just transition."</p>
<p>Second challenge is financing.</p>
<p>Europe, like other parts of the world, will need to redirect a relatively small portion of its production, around 1% to 2%, toward the green economy, particularly for new infrastructure, public tenders, research and development, industrial equipment renewal, and so on. Funding will come from both the private sector and public budgets.</p>
<p>Europe must stand up to ideologues who oppose increases in EU spending.</p>
<p>Facts must be considered.</p>
<p>The last great challenge is diplomatic.</p>
<p>L'Europe représente environ 9,1 % des émissions mondiales de dioxyde de carbone, quand la part de la Chine s'élève à 30 % et celle des États-Unis à 14 %.</p>
<p>Même si l'Europe parvient à mettre en place son pacte vert dans sa totalité, ce sera peine perdue si les autres régions du monde ne la rejoignent pas dans sa lutte.</p>
<p>Les dirigeants européens considèrent donc à juste titre que la diplomatie est fondamentale dans la réussite du pacte vert.</p>
<p>Prenons l'exemple de la Chine.</p>
<p>Après des décennies de croissance rapide, qui ont éliminé la pauvreté de masse, la Chine est devenue le premier émetteur mondial de CO2 (quoique ses rejets par habitant demeurent deux fois moindres que ceux des États-Unis).</p>
The China alone will determine the future of global climate.
On one hand, Chinese leaders know that their country is extremely vulnerable to climate change and risks diplomatic isolation if they do not make sufficient efforts to decarbonize; on the other hand, they must contend with the dangers of the ill-conceived cold war launched by America.
Hardliners within the Chinese government and coal lobbies resist, under pressure from the United States, decarbonization, especially since Trump rejects it himself.
European diplomacy could make a difference if it refuses to sign onto America’s covert measures to thwart China and instead offers China a positive and unambiguous partnership: working together to build sustainable infrastructure, development, and technology across Eurasia, within the framework of a Chinese Green Deal comparable to Europe’s.
Such a partnership would be immensely beneficial for Europe, China, and the dozen or so Eurasian countries that separate them, not to mention the world as a whole.
<p>L'Europe a fait un pas historique avec son plan ambitieux, mobilisateur et réalisable.</p>
<p>Le Green Deal est un puissant signal d'espoir dans un monde d'incertitudes et d'instabilité.</p>
